# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mccormick-place
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The first broadcast of *ATC* was fed to about 90 radio stations on May 3, 1971, with host Robert Conley.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] During the first week, these stations were not allowed to broadcast the feed "live" but could record it for later broadcast.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The first story was about the march on Washington, D.C., and the growing anti–Vietnam War protests taking place there.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] NPR chose to place its inaugural daily newscast at the afternoon commute timeslot instead of the morning because many of its affiliates at that time did not sign on for the day until mid-morning or afterward.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] It was not until 1979, by which time most affiliates had expanded their broadcast days to begin at 6 a.m. or earlier, that NPR premiered *Morning Edition*.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] On March 23, 2020, *ATC* launched ***The National Conversation***, a live call-in show addressing listener questions about the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The program aired from 9 p.m. to 10 p.m.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] ET on weeknights from the end of March through May 2020.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Similar to *Up First*, the podcast complement to the network's *Morning Edition* and *Weekend Edition*, NPR launched *Consider This* as a podcast companion to *ATC* on June 29, 2020, with *ATC* hosts providing in-depth analysis of a single story each weekday afternoon.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] National podcast episodes are supplemented in select areas by additional local reporting and analysis from journalists at various NPR member stations, such as Dallas-based KERA.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] *Consider This* is also the successor to NPR's weekday afternoon *Coronavirus Daily* podcast, which had published throughout the spring of 2020.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] It expanded to weekends on January 8, 2022, with episodes hosted by then-*WATC* host Michel Martin on Saturdays.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The podcast's weekend episode moved to Sundays in May 2023.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The format is less rigid than that of *Morning Edition*, with a wider array of type and length of stories.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The length of stories tends to be greater than *Morning Edition*, with some stories lasting for almost 23 minutes.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Certain types of personal interest stories are almost always covered within this limit; those relating to hard news or entertainment tend to last the standard three-and-a-half to four minutes.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The program begins with a theme song by Don Voegeli playing underneath a one-minute billboard of the stories to be covered during the hour.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Then the standard five-minute NPR newscast is delivered from one minute to six minutes past the hour.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The newscast offers a cutaway after three minutes (at four minutes past the hour), allowing stations to cover the last 2.5 minutes with evening rush-hour news and traffic reports.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] For those stations that run the newscast untouched, a 30-second music bed follows instead.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The first, or "A" segment, begins at :06:30 after the hour.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] It features important news stories, although not necessarily the most important news stories of the day.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Often it is here that the most significant interviews or developing stories are placed.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment A runs 11:29 in duration, and closes out at :18 after with a two-minute station break.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] At :20:35 past the hour, *ATC* picks back up with Segment B.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] This segment, which runs 8:24, features more news and analysis, and often contains lighter stories and commentary.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment B breaks for the half-hour at :29 past.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] The program goes into a one-minute local break.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] At the bottom of the hour, *ATC* resumes with a "host return".
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] In the 30-second return, the host or hosts discuss what's coming up in the remaining half-hour and intro the news.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] This is immediately followed by a 3:30 newscast which ends at :34 after the hour, followed by a one-minute local break.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment C kicks off at :35:35 past the hour, and runs 8:24.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Long feature stories are heard here, or as many as three shorter stories or commentaries may be heard as well.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment D occurs immediately after Segment C at :44 past the hour, and runs for four minutes.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment D is a designated cutaway for stations to run local commentary or features in lieu of the national segment.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment D ends at :48 after the hour, and another two-minute break ensues.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Occasionally, the show will "break format" and place a long, 12-minute story in Segments C and D without a local cutaway.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segment E starts at :50 after, and concludes the hour.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Unlike *Morning Edition*, there is no set format for this segment, although usually the second hour will contain an arts, culture, or lighter news story in this segment.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Other times, hard news otherwise not fitting in the program may be placed here.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Stations receive a preliminary rundown before each broadcast (usually a few minutes before 4:00 p.m.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Eastern) denoting the timing and placement of stories so they can schedule local content as appropriate.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] This rundown is updated as stories change until the feed ends at 10 p.m.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] As with *Morning Edition*, two hours of content are scheduled for each program.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Eastern, the feed repeats the earlier hours for the Midwest and West Coast, although information is updated through the evening as appropriate.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Major awards won by the show include the Ohio State Award, the Peabody Award, the Overseas Press Club Award, the DuPont Award, the American Women in Radio and Television Award, and the Robert F.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] In 1993, the show was inducted into the National Radio Hall of Fame, the first public radio program to be given that honor.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] In 2017, the first broadcast episode (from 1971) of *All Things Considered* was selected for preservation in the National Recording Registry by the Library of Congress.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Recordings in the collection are considered "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant".
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] ABC NewsRadio in Australia broadcasts a continuous hour of selected segments from each day's program between 12:00 and 13:00 Australian Eastern Standard Time Monday to Friday.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] Segments A to D are edited together omitting local NPR news inserts.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] NPR Berlin in Germany aired in the local German timeslot, live from the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/all-things-considered] From time to time, NPR produces and distributes short series of radio pieces.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:mccormick-place/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] The **Arie Crown Theater** is an entertainment venue situated on Lake Shore Drive in the Near South Side area of Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] Named after Lithuanian immigrant Arie Crown, who was the father of industrialist and philanthropist Henry Crown, it opened in 1960 with seating for 5,000 people, one of the largest seating capacities in Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] The theater is part of the McCormick Place convention facility, owned by the Metropolitan Pier and Exposition Authority.
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] The theatre was damaged by a fire in 1967 and was closed until 1971.
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] After re-opening in January for Mahalia Jackson's funeral, the Arie Crown has, for more than five decades, presented classical, R&B, and rock music, along with musicals and plays.
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] Blige, David Bowie, Chicago, and Katt Williams, among others.
[src:mccormick-place/arie-crown-theater] In more recent years, the acoustics have been improved by changing the proportions of the auditorium and staging area, and this has reduced the seating capacity to 4,188 people.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The **Art Institute of Chicago** is a private, nonprofit art museum in Grant Park, Chicago, Illinois, United States.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Founded in 1879, it is one of the oldest and largest art museums in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum is based in the Art Institute of Chicago Building in Chicago's Grant Park.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Its collection, stewarded by 11 curatorial departments, includes works such as Georges Seurat's *A Sunday on La Grande Jatte*, Pablo Picasso's *The Old Guitarist*, Edward Hopper's *Nighthawks*, and Grant Wood's *American Gothic*.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Its permanent collection of nearly 300,000 works of art is augmented by more than 30 special exhibitions mounted yearly that present curatorial and scientific research.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The land of the institute is publicly owned by the city of Chicago and administered by the Chicago Park District.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] As a research institution, the Art Institute also has a conservation and conservation science department, five conservation laboratories, and Ryerson and Burnham Libraries, one of the nation's largest art history and architecture libraries.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum's building was constructed for the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition and, due to the growth of the collection, several additions have occurred since.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Modern Wing, designed by Renzo Piano, is the most recent expansion, and when it opened in 2009 it increased the museum's footprint to nearly one million square feet.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] This made it the second largest art museum in the United States, after the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The School of the Art Institute of Chicago is legally part of the Art Institute of Chicago, making it one of the few remaining unified arts institutions in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 1866, a group of 35 artists founded the **Chicago Academy of Design** in a studio on Dearborn Street, with the intent to run a free school with its own art gallery.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The organization was modeled after European art academies, such as the Royal Academy, with Academicians and Associate Academicians.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The academy's charter was granted in March 1867.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Classes started in 1868, meeting every day at a cost of $10 per month.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The academy's success enabled it to build a new home for the school, a five-story stone building on 66 West Adams Street, which opened on November 22, 1870.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] When the Great Chicago Fire destroyed the building in 1871, the academy was thrown into debt.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Attempts to continue despite the loss by using rented facilities failed.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Members tried to rescue the ailing institution by making deals with local businessmen, before some finally abandoned it in 1879 to found a new organization, named the **Chicago Academy of Fine Arts**.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] When the Chicago Academy of Design went bankrupt the same year, the new Chicago Academy of Fine Arts bought its assets at auction.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 1882, the Chicago Academy of Fine Arts changed its name to the current Art Institute of Chicago and elected as its first president the banker and philanthropist Charles L.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Hutchinson, who "is arguably the single most important individual to have shaped the direction and fortunes of the Art Institute of Chicago".
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Hutchinson was a director of many prominent Chicago organizations, including the University of Chicago, and would transform the Art Institute into a world-class museum during his presidency, which he held until his death in 1924.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Also in 1882, the organization purchased a lot on the southwest corner of Michigan Avenue and Van Buren Street for $45,000.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The existing commercial building on that property was used for the organization's headquarters, and a new addition was constructed behind it to provide gallery space and to house the school's facilities.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] By January 1885 the trustees recognized the need to provide additional space for the organization's growing collection, and to this end purchased the vacant lot directly south on Michigan Avenue.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The commercial building was demolished, and the noted architect John Wellborn Root was hired by Hutchinson to design a building that would create an "impressive presence" on Michigan Avenue, and these facilities opened to great fanfare in 1887.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] With the announcement of the World's Columbian Exposition to be held in 1892–93, the Art Institute pressed for a building on the lakefront to be constructed for the fair, but to be used by the institute afterwards.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The city agreed, and the building was completed in time for the second year of the fair.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Construction costs were met by selling the Michigan/Van Buren property.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] On October 31, 1893, the institute moved into the new building.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] For the opening reception on December 8, 1893, Theodore Thomas and the Chicago Symphony Orchestra performed.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] From the early 1900s to the 1960s the school offered, with the Logan Family (members of the board), the Logan Medal of the Arts, an award which became one of the most distinguished awards presented to artists in the U.S.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Between 1959 and 1970, the institute was a key site in the movement to gain mainstream gallery acceptance for art photography and documentary photography, under curator Hugh Edwards and his assistants.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] As director of the museum starting in the early 1980s, James N.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Wood conducted a major expansion of its collection and oversaw a major renovation and expansion project for its facilities.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] As "one of the most respected museum leaders in the country", as described by *The New York Times*, Wood created major exhibitions of works by Paul Gauguin, Claude Monet, and Vincent van Gogh that set records for attendance at the museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The institute began construction of "The Modern Wing", an addition situated on the southwest corner of Columbus and Monroe in the early 21st century.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The project, designed by Pritzker Prize–winning architect Renzo Piano, was completed and officially opened to the public on May 16, 2009.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The 264,000-square-foot (24,500 m2) building addition made the Art Institute the second-largest art museum in the United States.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The building houses the museum's world-renowned collections of 20th and 21st century art, specifically modern European painting and sculpture, contemporary art, architecture and design, and photography.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In its inaugural survey in 2014, travel review website and forum, Tripadvisor, reviewed millions of travelers' surveys and named the Art Institute the world's best museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum received perhaps the largest gift of art in its history in 2015.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Collectors Stefan Edlis and Gael Neeson donated a "collection [that] is among the world's greatest groups of postwar Pop art ever assembled".
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The donation includes works by Andy Warhol, Jasper Johns, Cy Twombly, Jeff Koons, Charles Ray, Richard Prince, Cindy Sherman, Roy Lichtenstein and Gerhard Richter.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum agreed to keep the donated work on display for at least 50 years.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In June 2018, the museum received a $50 million donation, the largest single announced unrestricted monetary donation in its history.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In September 2024, the Art Institute of Chicago announced a $75 million donation from collectors Aaron I.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Fleischman and Lin Lougheed, marking the largest naming gift in the museum's history.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] This contribution is designated for the development of The Aaron I.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Fleischman and Lin Lougheed Building, intended to showcase the museum's extensive collection of late 19th-century, modern, and contemporary art.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In February 2025, the Art Institute of Chicago received a significant donation from collectors Jeffrey and Carol Horvitz, comprising nearly 2,000 drawings, 200 paintings, and 50 sculptures by renowned French artists such as Jacques-Louis David and François Boucher.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] This collection, amassed over four decades, spans the 16th to 19th centuries, with a focus on Neoclassicism.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] It is principally known for one of the United States' finest collections of paintings produced in Western culture.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute's African Art and Indian Art of the Americas collections are on display across two galleries in the south end of the Michigan Avenue building.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The African collection includes more than 400 works that span the continent, highlighting ceramics, garments, masks, and jewelry.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Amerindian collection includes Native North American art and Mesoamerican and Andean works.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] From pottery to textiles, the collection brings together a wide array of objects that seek to illustrate the thematic and aesthetic focuses of art spanning the Americas.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute's American Art collection contains some of the best-known works in the American canon, including Edward Hopper's *Nighthawks*, Grant Wood's *American Gothic*, and Mary Cassatt's *The Child's Bath*.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The collection ranges from colonial silver to modern and contemporary paintings.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum purchased *Nighthawks* in 1942 for $3,000; its acquisition "launched" the painting into "immense popular recognition".
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Considered an "icon of American culture", *Nighthawks* is perhaps Hopper's most famous painting, and one of the most recognizable images in American art.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Also well known, *American Gothic* has been in the museum's collection since 1930 and was only loaned outside of North America for the first time in 2016.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Wood's painting depicts what has been called "the most famous couple in the world", a dour, rural-American, father and daughter.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] It was entered into a contest at the Art Institute in 1930, and although not a favorite of some, it won a medal and was acquired by the museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute's ancient collection spans nearly 4,000 years of art and history, showcasing Greek, Etruscan, Roman, and Egyptian sculpture, mosaics, pottery, jewelry, glass, and bronze and a robust and well-maintained collection of ancient coins.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] There are around 5,000 works in the collection, offering a comprehensive survey of the ancient and medieval Mediterranean world, beginning with the third millennium B.C. and extending to the Byzantine Empire.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The collection also holds the mummy and mummy case of Paankhenamun.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Department of Architecture and Design holds more than 140,000 works, from models to drawings from the 1870s to the present day.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The collection covers landscape architecture, structural engineering, and industrial design, including the works of Frank Lloyd Wright, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, and Le Corbusier.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute's Asian collection spans nearly 5,000 years, including significant works and objects from China, Korea, Japan, India, Southeast Asia, and the Near and Middle East.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] There are 35,000 objects in the collection, showcasing bronzes, ceramics, jades, textiles, screens, woodcuts, and sculptures.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] One gallery in particular attempts to mimic the quiet and meditative way in which Japanese screens are traditionally viewed.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute's collection of European decorative arts includes some 25,000 objects of furniture, ceramics, metalwork, glass, enamel, and ivory from 1100 AD to the present day.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Both the paperweights and the Thorne Rooms are located on the ground floor of the museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum is most famous for its collections of Impressionist and Post-Impressionist paintings, widely regarded as one of the finest collections outside of France.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Highlights include more than 30 paintings by Claude Monet, including six of his *Haystacks* and a number of *Water Lilies*.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The pointillist masterpiece, which also inspired a musical and was featured in *Ferris Bueller's Day Off*, Georges Seurat's *Sunday Afternoon on La Grande Jatte—1884,* is prominently displayed.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Additionally, Henri Matisse's *Bathers by a River*, is an important example of his work.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Highlights of non-French paintings of the Impressionist and Post-Impressionist collection include Vincent van Gogh's *Bedroom in Arles* and *Self-portrait*, 1887.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In the mid-1930s, the Art Institute received a gift of over one hundred works of art from Annie Swan Coburn ("Mr. and Mrs.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Lewis Larned Coburn Memorial Collection").
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The "Coburn Renoirs" became the core of the Art Institute's Impressionist painting collection.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The collection also includes the Medieval and Renaissance Art, Arms, and Armor holdings, including the George F.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Harding Collection of arms and armor, and three centuries of Old Masters works.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum's collection of modern and contemporary art was significantly augmented when collectors Stefan Edlis and Gael Neeson gifted 40 plus master works to the department in 2015.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Pablo Picasso's *Old Guitarist*, Henri Matisse's *Bathers by a River*, Constantin Brâncuși's *Golden Bird*, and René Magritte's *Time Transfixed* are highlights of the modern galleries, located on the third floor of the Modern Wing.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The contemporary installation, located on the second floor, contains works by Andy Warhol, Cindy Sherman, Cy Twombly, Jackson Pollock, Jasper Johns, and other significant modern and contemporary artists.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute did not officially establish a photography collection until 1949, when Georgia O'Keeffe donated a significant portion of the Alfred Stieglitz collection to the museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Since then, the museum's collection has grown to approximately 20,000 works spanning the history of the artform from its inception in 1839 to the present.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The print and drawings collection began with a donation by Elizabeth S.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Stickney of 460 works in 1887, and was organized into its own department of the museum in 1911.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Their holdings have subsequently grown to 11,500 drawings and 60,000 prints, ranging from 15th-century works to contemporary.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The collection contains a strong group of the works of Albrecht Dürer, Rembrandt van Rijn, Francisco Goya, and James McNeill Whistler.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Because works on paper are sensitive to light and degrade quickly, the works are on display infrequently in order to keep them in good condition for as long as possible.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Department of Textiles has more than 13,000 textiles and 66,000 sample swatches in total, covering an array of cultures from 300 BC to the present.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] From English needlework to Japanese garments to American quilts, the collection presents a diverse group of objects, including contemporary works and fiber art.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Other notable works are in the collection but the following examples are ones in the public domain and for which pictures are available.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2018, as it redesigned its website, the Art Institute released images of 52,438 of its public domain works, under the Creative Commons Zero (CC0) licence.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The current building complex at 111 South Michigan Avenue is the third address for the Art Institute.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute's entrance on Michigan Avenue is guarded by two bronze lion statues created by Edward Kemeys.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The lions were unveiled on May 10, 1894, each weighing more than two tons.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The sculptor gave them unofficial names: the south lion "stands in an attitude of defiance", and the north lion is "on the prowl".
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] When a Chicago sports team plays in the championships of their respective league (i.e. the Super Bowl or Stanley Cup Finals, not the entire playoffs), the lions are frequently dressed in that team's uniform.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Evergreen wreaths are placed around their necks during the Christmas season.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The east entrance of the museum is marked by the stone arch entrance to the old Chicago Stock Exchange.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Designed by Louis Sullivan in 1894, the Exchange was demolished in 1972, but salvaged portions of the original trading room were brought to the Art Institute and reconstructed.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute building has the unusual property of straddling open-air railroad tracks.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Two stories of gallery space connect the east and west buildings while the Metra Electric and South Shore lines operate below.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The lower level of gallery space was formerly the windowless Gunsaulus hall, but is now home to the Alsdorf Galleries showcasing Indian, Southeast Asian and Himalayan Art.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] During renovation, windows facing north toward Millennium Park were added.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The gallery space was designed by Renzo Piano in conjunction with his design of the Modern Wing and features the same window screening used there to protect the art from direct sunlight.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The upper level formerly held the modern European galleries, but was renovated in 2008 and now features the Impressionist and Post-Impressionist galleries.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In September 2024, the museum announced a gift of $75 million for a new gallery building or wing named for benefactors Aaron I.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The gallery is intended to increase space for 19th century, modern, and contemporary art.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The design and placement of the new gallery or gallery building are yet to be decided.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Located on the ground floor of the museum is the Ryerson & Burnham Libraries.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Libraries' collections cover all periods of art, but is most known for its extensive collection of 18th to 20th century architecture.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] It serves the museum staff, college and university students, and is also open to the general public.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Friends of the Libraries, a support group for the Libraries, offers events and special tours for its members.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] On May 16, 2009, the Art Institute opened the Modern Wing, the largest expansion in the museum's history.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The 264,000-square-foot (24,500 m2) addition, designed by Renzo Piano, makes the Art Institute the second-largest museum in the US.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The architect of record in the City of Chicago for this building was Interactive Design.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Wing also houses contemporary art from after 1960; new photography, video media, architecture and design galleries including original renderings by Frank Lloyd Wright, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe and Bruce Goff; temporary exhibition space; shops and classrooms; and a cafe.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In addition, the Nichols Bridgeway connects a sculpture garden on the roof of the new wing with the adjacent Millennium Park to the north and a courtyard designed by Gustafson Guthrie Nichol.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2009, the Modern Wing won at the Chicago Innovation Awards.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] During 2009, attendance was around 2 million—up 33 percent from 2008—in addition to a total of approximately 100,000 museum memberships.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Despite a 25 percent boost in museum admission fees, the Modern Wing was a major catalyst for a rise in visitor traffic.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2022, the museum welcomed 1.04 million visitors, an increase of 20 percent from 2021, but still well below 2018 attendance (before the COVID-19 pandemic).
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] It was ranked tenth among the most-visited museums in the United States, and was the sixth most-visited U.S. art museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] As of 2011, the Art Institute continues to rebuild its $783 million endowment since the recession.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In June 2008, its endowment was $827 million.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] As of 2012, the museum is rated A1 by Moody's, its fifth-highest grade, in part reflecting the museum's pension and retirement liabilities; Standard & Poor's rates the museum A+, fifth-best.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In October 2012, the Art Institute sold about $100 million of taxable and tax-exempt bonds partly to shore-up unfunded pension obligations.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The $294 million extension in 2009 was the culmination of a $385 million fundraising campaign—roughly $300 million for design and construction and $85 million for the endowment.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Around $370 million were raised primarily from private patrons in Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2011, the Art Institute received a $10 million gift from the Jaharis Family Foundation to renovate and expand galleries devoted to Greek, Roman and Byzantine art, and to support acquisitions and special exhibitions of that art.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2016 the Art Institute received a $35 million gift from Dorothy Braude Edinburg, a longtime supporter.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 1990, the Art Institute of Chicago sold 11 works at auction, including paintings by Claude Monet, Pablo Picasso, Amedeo Modigliani, Maurice Utrillo and Edgar Degas, to raise the $12 million purchase price of a bronze sculpture, *Golden Bird*, by Constantin Brâncuși.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] At the time, the sculpture was owned by the Arts Club of Chicago, which was selling it to buy a new gallery for its other works.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2005, the museum sold two paintings by Marc Chagall and Pierre-Auguste Renoir at Sotheby's.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2011, it auctioned two Picassos (*Sur l'impériale traversant la Seine* (1901) and *Verre et pipe* (1919)), Henri Matisse's *Femme au fauteuil* (1919), and Georges Braque's *Nature morte à la guitare (rideaux rouge)* (1938) at Christie's in London.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2002, the Art Institute of Chicago filed suit alleging fraud by a small Dallas firm called Integral Investment Management, along with related parties.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The museum, which put $43 million of its endowment into funds run by the defendants, claimed that it faced losses of up to 90% on the investments after they soured.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2010, the year after the opening of its massive Modern Wing, the Art Institute of Chicago sued the engineering firm Ove Arup for $10 million over what it said were flaws in the concrete floors and air-circulation systems.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2021, the Art Institute ended its unpaid volunteer docents program to move to a paid model.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] A collection of approximately 500 objects from Nepal, India and elsewhere in Asia that was donated to the Art Institute by trustee Marilynn Alsdorf in 1989; certain objects from this collection have been contested.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2000, the Art Institute reached a settlement agreement with the heirs of Federico Gentili Di Giuseppe concerning a restitution claim for a 17th century sculpture by Francesco Mochi.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2001, the heirs of Holocaust victim Max Silberberg reached a settlement agreement concerning Gustav Courbet's *The Rock in Hautepierre.* The Art Institute had acquired the Courbet from the dealer Paul Rosenberg in 1967.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2023, the Manhattan District Attorney's Office moved to seize Egon Schiele paintings from several museums on the grounds that they had been looted by the Nazis from Fritz Grünbaum, who was killed in the Holocaust.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The paintings included, *Russian War Prisoner,* a watercolor in the Art Institute.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute continues to hold the work, as it is contesting the seizure in court.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] According to its investigation, it acquired the watercolor drawing in 1966 from an American art dealer through a proper provenance from Grünbaum's legal heir, and it also argues that the claim is time-barred because Grünbaum's heirs were aware.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In February 2024, the Manhattan District Attorney filed a motion accusing the Art Institute of "ignoring evidence of an elaborate fraud undertaken to conceal that the artwork had been looted".
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] According to *The New York Times*, the court filing provided detailed evidence that provenance documents provided by the Swiss art dealer Eberhard W.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Kornfeld contained forged signatures or were altered long after he came into possession of the paintings and sold them to other art dealers in the mid-1950s; however, the Art Institute disputed this claim.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Court hearings on the matter took place in 2024.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The Art Institute of Chicago created a dedicated Provenance Research Department in 2020 to conduct provenance research across the entire collection, as well as for acquisitions and loans.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In 2024, Jacques Schumacher was recruited to lead the provenance team.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In June 2024, the Art Institute of Chicago returned a 12th-century sandstone pilaster to Thailand.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The artifact, depicting the Hindu deity Krishna lifting Mount Govardhana, was originally acquired by the museum in 1967 and believed to be from Angkor, Cambodia.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] However, provenance research determined that it originated from the Phanom Rung temple in northeastern Thailand.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] This discovery led to discussions with Thai authorities and the subsequent repatriation of the piece.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] On March 3, 2025, the Art Institute of Chicago announced that it had returned a 12th-century Nepali sculpture, *Buddha Sheltered by the Serpent King Muchalinda*, to the government of Nepal after provenance research confirmed it had been stolen from Guita Bahi in the Kathmandu Valley.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The sculpture, carved from schist, had been on display at the museum since 1997.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In April 2025 a judge ordered the museum to restitute a Nazi-looted Schiele drawing to the heirs of Holocaust victim Fritz Grunbaum following its seizure *in situ*.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In May the museum appealed the decision, saying it was confident it owned the artwork based on its own provenance research.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In June a New York court validated the seizure of the painting by The Antiquities Trafficking Unit (“ATU”) of the Office of the District Attorney of New York County.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] In *Ferris Bueller's Day Off* (1986), the Art Institute of Chicago scene is a quiet, contemplative moment in an otherwise fast-paced film.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Ferris Bueller (Matthew Broderick), his girlfriend Sloane (Mia Sara), and his best friend Cameron (Alan Ruck) visit the museum during their day of adventure in Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Set to The Dream Academy's instrumental cover of *Please Please Please Let Me Get What I Want*, the sequence showcases some of the museum's most famous artworks.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The trio walks hand in hand through the museum's grand halls before pausing to admire iconic pieces.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Ferris and Sloane share a tender moment in front of Marc Chagall's *America Windows*, while Cameron becomes mesmerized by Georges Seurat's *A Sunday on La Grande Jette*.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] As the camera zooms in on the small painted dots, Cameron's gaze intensifies, reflecting his growing existential crisis.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The scene, devoid of dialogue, serves as a moment of reflection.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Ferris and Sloane embrace, reinforcing their carefree love, while Cameron, often plagued by self-doubt, appears lost in thought.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] His fixation on the Seurat painting subtly foreshadows his later emotional breakdown.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Director John Hughes, a Chicago native, has said this sequence was a love letter to the museum, emphasizing art's ability to move and transform individuals.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The scene stands out in the film for its quiet beauty, offering a moment of introspection amid the comedic chaos of Ferris's day off.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Hughes's commentary on the sequence was used as a reference point by journalist Hadley Freeman in a discussion of the Republican presidential primary candidates in 2011.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The 1970 Parker Brothers board game Masterpiece features paintings from the Art Institute of Chicago's collection.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The game, designed for players to bid on and trade famous artworks while attempting to avoid forgeries, includes reproductions of several iconic works housed in the museum.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] Notable paintings featured in the game include Georges Seurat's A Sunday on La Grande Jatte, Vincent van Gogh's The Bedroom, and Grant Wood's American Gothic.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The game was one of the first major board games to introduce fine art to a mainstream audience in an interactive format.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] By using real paintings from the Art Institute's collection, Masterpiece played a role in exposing a broader public to well-known artworks.
[src:mccormick-place/art-institute-of-chicago] The game remains a nostalgic classic and has been reissued multiple times with different artwork selections, but the original 1970 edition is closely associated with the Art Institute of Chicago's holdings.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] A **ballroom** or **ballhall** is a large room inside a building, the primary purpose of which is holding large formal parties called *balls*.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] Traditionally, most balls were held in private residences; many mansions and palaces, especially historic mansions and palaces, contain one or more ballrooms.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] In other large houses, a large room such as the main drawing room, long gallery, or hall may double as a ballroom, but a good ballroom should have the right type of flooring, such as hardwood flooring or stone flooring (usually marble or stone)..
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] For most styles of modern dance, a wooden sprung floor offers the best surface.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] In later times, the term "ballroom" has been used to describe nightclubs where customers dance; the Top Rank Suites in the United Kingdom, for example, were also often referred to as ballrooms.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] The phrase "having a ball" has grown to encompass many events where person(s) are having fun, not just dancing.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] Ballrooms are generally quite large, and may have ceilings higher than other rooms in the same building.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] The large amount of space for dancing, as well as the highly formal tone of events, has given rise to ballroom dancing.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] The largest balls are now nearly always held in public buildings, and many hotels have a ballroom.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] They are also designed large to help the sound of orchestras carry well throughout the whole room.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] The few teams that did that helped promote the businesses that afforded their services by providing affordable entertainment with both a good sporting match and a fun dance for the audience to attend in themselves soon afterward.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] A special case is the annual Vienna Opera Ball, where, just for one night, the auditorium of the Vienna State Opera is turned into a large ballroom.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] On the eve of the event, the rows of seats are removed from the stalls, and a new floor, level with the stage, is built.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] Sometimes ballrooms have stages in the front of the room where the host or a special guest can speak.
[src:mccormick-place/ballroom] That stage can also be used for instrumentalists and musical performers.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The **Batcave** is a fictional subterranean cave appearing in the *Batman* franchise, first created for the 1943 *Batman* film serial.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It is the headquarters of the superhero Batman and his partners, and located beneath Wayne Manor, personal residence of Batman's secret identity Bruce Wayne.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Over the decades, the cave has been expanded to include a vast trophy room, supercomputer, and forensics lab.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] There has been little consistency as to the floor plan of the Batcave or its contents.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The design has varied from artist to artist and it is not unusual for the same artist to draw the cave layout differently in various issues.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave first became part of the Batman mythos in the 1943 15-chapter serial *Batman* starring Lewis Wilson.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In this version, as later in the comics, it is a small cave with a desk and rock walls lit up by candles.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Behind the desk is a large black bat symbol.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Bats were depicted as flying around the cave, although only their shadows are visible.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Batman uses these bats as a scare tactic to make an apprehended enemy reveal information.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] To prevent the enemy from escaping, an iron door covers the exit.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The comics originally only portrayed a secret tunnel that ran underground between Wayne Manor and a dusty old barn where the Batmobile was kept.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Later, in *Batman* #12 (August–September 1942), Bill Finger mentioned "secret underground hangars".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In 1943, the writers of the first Batman film serial gave Batman a complete underground crime lab and introduced it in the second chapter, entitled "The Bat's Cave".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The entrance was via a secret passage through a grandfather clock and included bats flying around.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Bob Kane, who was on the film set, mentioned this to Finger who was going to be the initial scripter on the Batman daily newspaper strip.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Finger included with his script a clipping from *Popular Mechanics* that featured a detailed cross-section of underground hangars.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Kane used this clipping as a guide, adding a study, crime lab, workshop, hangar and garage.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] This illustration appeared in the *Batman* "dailies" on October 29, 1943, in a strip entitled "The Bat Cave!".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In this early version, the cave was described as Batman's underground study and, like the other rooms, was just a small alcove with a desk and filing cabinets.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Like in the film serial, Batman's symbol was carved into the rock behind the desk and had a candle in the middle of it.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The entrance was via a bookcase which led to a secret elevator.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave was also featured and expanded on in the 1949 serial *Batman and Robin*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In this serial, there are filing cabinets and the cave now has a crime lab built in.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The cave also contains the first incarnation of a batphone.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave made its comic book debut in *Detective Comics* #83 in January 1944.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The cave was discovered and used long before by Bruce Wayne's ancestors as a storehouse as well as a means of transporting escaped slaves during the Civil War era.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Bruce rediscovered the caves as a boy when he fell through a dilapidated well on his estate, but did not consider it as a potential base of operations until returning to Gotham to become Batman.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In earlier versions of the story, Bruce discovered the cave as an adult.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Upon his initial foray into crime-fighting, Bruce used the caves as a sanctum and to store his then-minimal equipment.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] As time went on, Bruce found the place ideal to create a stronghold for his war against crime, and has incorporated a plethora of equipment as well as expanding the cave for specific uses.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It can be reached through a secret door in Wayne Manor itself, which is almost always depicted as in the main study, often behind a grandfather clock which unlocks when the hands are set to the time that Bruce Wayne's parents were murdered, 10:48 pm.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In *Batman* (1966), the cave entrance is behind a bookcase that hides firepoles which was opened when Bruce Wayne activated a control switch hidden in a bust of William Shakespeare, while Wayne's butler, Alfred Pennyworth uses a separate service elevator.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] An entrance under Bruce Wayne's chair in his office in Wayne Enterprises, as shown in *Batman Forever*, connects to a mile-long tunnel that Bruce travels through in a high-speed personal transportation capsule.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In *Batman Begins* and *The Dark Knight Rises*, the cave is accessible through a secret door disguised as part of a large display case and is unlocked by pressing a sequence of keys on the nearby grand piano.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Another secret entrance, covered by a waterfall, pond, hologram, or a camouflaged door, allows access to a service road for the Batmobile.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Another alternate entrance is the dry well where Bruce originally discovered the Batcave, highlighted especially during the *Knightfall* comic book storyline.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] At one point, Dick Grayson and Tim Drake use the dry well to get into the cave, which they had been locked out of by Azrael during his time as Batman, and Bruce Wayne used it to infiltrate the cave and confront the insane Valley in the final battle between the two men for the title of the Batman.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Lured into the narrow tunnel, Valley was forced to remove the massive Bat-armor he had developed, thus allowing Wayne to force Valley to remit his claim to the title.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave serves as Batman's secret headquarters and the command center, where he monitors all crisis points in Gotham City, as well as the rest of the world.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The cave's centerpiece is a supercomputer whose specs are on par with any of those used by leading national security agencies; it permits global surveillance and also connects to a massive information network as well as storing vast amounts of information.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] A series of satellite link-ups allows easy access to Batman's information network anywhere around the globe.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The systems are protected against unauthorized access, and any attempt to breach their security immediately sends an alert to Batman or Oracle.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It also has medical facilities as well as various areas used in training exercises for Batman and his allies.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The cave houses Batman's vast array of specialized vehicles, foremost being the Batmobile in all its incarnations.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Other vehicles within the complex include various motorcycles, air- and watercraft such as the Batplane, a single-occupant supersonic jet, and the Subway Rocket.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] During the *Cataclysm* storyline, the cave is seriously damaged in an earthquake, with the Bat-family relocating most of the trophies and equipment in the cave to offsite storage to conceal Batman's identity.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] During the later reconstruction, Wayne Manor incorporates additional safeguards against future quakes and even a potential nuclear catastrophe, outfitting the cave as a virtual bomb shelter or an enhanced panic room.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The city's earthquake alters the caverns of the Batcave, with eight new levels now making up Batman's secret refuge of high-tech laboratory, library, training areas, storage areas, and vehicle accesses.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It also includes an "island" computer platform with seven linked Cray T932 mainframes and a state-of-the-art hologram projector.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] There is also a selection of retractable glass maps within the computer platform.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Kevlar shieldings are prepared to protect the cave's computer systems from seismic activity.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] With the cave's various facilities spread amid limestone stalactites and stalagmites, Batman builds retractable multi-walkway bridges, stairs, elevators, and poles to access its facilities.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave is rigged with a sophisticated security system to prevent all measure of infiltration.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The security measures include motion sensors, silent alarms, steel and lead mechanical doors which could lock a person in or out, and a security mode which is specifically designed to stop if not eliminate all Justice League members in the event that any of them go rogue.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The cave stores unique memorabilia items collected from the various cases Batman has worked on over the years.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Originally, these were stored in a room designed just for them; it was explained that Batman and Robin took one memento from each case.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Later, the trophies were shown to be in the large main area of the cave, residing among the rest of the Batcave's furnishings.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The most regularly featured trophies are a full-size animatronic *Tyrannosaurus rex*, a giant replica of a Lincoln penny, and an oversized Joker playing card.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Rex* comes from an adventure on "Dinosaur Island" (*Batman* #35 1946); the penny was originally a trophy from Batman's encounter with a penny-obsessed villain named the Penny Plunderer (*World's Finest Comics* #30 1947), but was later retconned into being from an encounter with Two-Face.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Other "keepsakes" in the cave come from "The Thousand and One Trophies of Batman!" (*Detective Comics* #158, 1950).
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] These three stories were reprinted in *Batman* #256.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] There is also a glass case display of Jason Todd's Robin costume as a memorial to him, with the epitaph "A Good Soldier", which remains even after Todd's resurrection.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Barbara Gordon's Batgirl costume also remains on display.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] After the *Flashpoint* comic book storyline, a letter written by a Thomas Wayne from an alternate timeline addressed to Bruce Wayne has lain in a display case, as a reminder of Thomas's love for his son and encouraging him to move on from his past.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The letter was destroyed by the reborn Eobard Thawne as a way to hurt Bruce for Thomas's attempt to kill him.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] When Jean-Paul Valley takes over the role of Batman, Tim Drake uses an abandoned barn nearby Wayne Manor and his own house to hide his own land vehicle, the Red Bird, and in time it becomes his own safe house after he adds his computer and portable equipment.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] After Bane's attack during the *Knightfall* story arc, Bruce Wayne swore that he would never be caught unprepared to defend Gotham City ever again.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] When Dick Grayson became Batman during the *Prodigal* storyline, Bruce established satellite Batcaves throughout the city to act as safehouses.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave from the 1966 television series was portrayed in the corresponding film released after the first television season.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] A new version of the Batcave appears in *The Batman*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave is an old Wayne Terminus railway station into his hidden headquarters, accessed through a series of secret tunnels underneath Wayne Tower.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave is featured in *The Lego Batman Movie*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] This version of the Batcave is larger and contains many versions of the Batmobile, Bat-themed vehicles and Batsuits.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It is controlled by Batman's sentient, HAL-9000-like, Batcomputer (voiced by Siri), nicknamed 'Puter'.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The 1960s live-action Batman TV series featured the Batcave extensively, and portrayed it as a large but well-lit cavern containing an atomic power generator, a chemistry lab, punch-card computers, and other electronic crime-fighting devices, almost always prominently labeled with their function.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In this incarnation, it primarily served as a crime lab and garage for the Batmobile.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In this version, the Batcave is accessed from Wayne Manor via two Bat-Poles, which are hidden behind a bookcase that can be opened by turning a switch hidden inside a bust of Shakespeare.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] When Bruce and Dick slide down these Bat-Poles, they are instantly outfitted in their costumes before reaching the landing pads at the bottom.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Bat-Poles can also be used to lift Bruce and Dick up from the Batcave to Wayne Manor by use of the steamjet-propelled landing pads.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave is also accessible via a service elevator used by Alfred.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Bat-Cave was first seen in animation in episodes of *The Batman/Superman Hour*, *Super Friends*, and *The New Adventures of Batman*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In these cartoons, the Batcomputer is present as usual.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The voice of the Batcomputer was portrayed by Lou Scheimer in *The New Adventures of Batman*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In the *Batman: The Animated Series* episode "Beware the Gray Ghost", the Batcave is revealed to be a replica of the lair used by the Gray Ghost, a film character and Bruce's idol.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Bats are seen flying freely in the cave, with large naturally elevated platforms on which Robin practices balance.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Batman's numerous crime-fighting vehicles are seen parked in an adjacent compartment to the Batcave, with an adjoining subterranean garage which stores Bruce Wayne's car collection.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The future Batcave of *Batman Beyond* houses replicas of Batman's enemies (both as wax dummies and robot combat trainers), and a display case with the many permutations of costumes of Robin, Batgirl, Nightwing, and Batman himself.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In *Batman Beyond 2.0*, Terry McGinnis no longer uses the Batcave following an argument with Bruce.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] After arriving in the universe controlled by the Justice Lords, Terry encounters his alternate universe counterpart, T, who is a member of the Jokerz.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Terry and T arrive at Wayne Manor to find that it had been destroyed by the Justice Lords.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Following the defeat of Lord Superman, T and Dick Grayson of the Justice Lords universe begin rebuilding the Batcave.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave appears in *Batman: The Brave and the Bold*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] This version displays numerous trophies that reference the 1960s *Batman* series, namely a giant clam and slot-machine-themed electric chair.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] A future version appears in "Last Bat on Earth!", where it is inhabited by a group of humanoid "Man-Bats".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave makes a minor appearance in the *Teen Titans* episode "Haunted".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave appears in the *Young Justice* episode "Downtime".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In this version, the entrance to the Bat Cave is hidden behind a large fireplace in Bruce Wayne's trophy room.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Batman brings unconscious guests in, such as Man-Bat and Manhunter, for questioning.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In the series finale, Deathstroke infiltrates the Batcave and attempts to destroy it until Batman stops him.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave appears in the *Teen Titans Go!* episode, "Sidekick," where Robin is tasked with watching over the Batcave while Batman is away and the Teen Titans show up and start messing with the Batcave's gadgets, costumes and trophies.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave makes continuous appearances in later episodes.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In the TV series *Batwoman*, Bruce has a Batcave in Wayne Towers which is used by his cousin Kate, Luke Fox and later Ryan Wilder when she takes over the Batwoman position.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It was later revealed that a Batmobile was stored behind a hidden wall which Ryan used during her tenure as Batwoman.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It is overseen by the Batcomputer (voiced by Kimberly Brooks) and original character M.O.E.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave appears as a level in *Mortal Kombat vs.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] A new version of the Batcave appears as a level in *Injustice 2*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] This version was originally the Gotham Underground Subway built by Bruce's great-grandfather.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] It is also where Bruce keeps his communications and surveillance hub, Brother Eye.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave appears in *Lego Batman 2: DC Super Heroes*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] In the 2009 video game *Batman: Arkham Asylum,* Batman can access a secret auxiliary Batcave hidden within the cave system beneath Arkham Island after the Joker takes control of the asylum.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] This Batcave is small and fairly spartan compared to its comic counterpart, containing only two small platforms, a Batcomputer, and one of Batman's Batwing planes.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Near the end of the game this cave was partially destroyed by Poison Ivy.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Although not featured in the main story, the Batcave does appear as a downloadable challenge map in *Batman: Arkham City*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] During the main story, Batman is able to access the Batcomputer's database via his batsuit and can upload data to Alfred who can analyze it using the Batcomputer back at the Batcave.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] The Batcave is accessible in the main campaign of *Batman: Arkham Origins*.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] From the cave, the player can use the Batwing fast travel system, switch to alternate skins and enter the challenge map rooms as opposed to selecting from the main menu as in previous Arkham games.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] Although the Batcave is not accessible in *Batman: Arkham Knight*, Alfred coordinates all activity from it.
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] He also activates the Knightfall Protocol from within the cave using Bruce's voice authorization password "Martha".
[src:mccormick-place/bat-cave] When Wayne Manor was destroyed after Bruce activates the protocol, it is unknown if the Batcave survived.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] A **bus lane** or **bus-only lane** is a lane restricted to buses, generally to speed up public transport that would be otherwise held up by traffic congestion.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The related term **busway** describes a roadway completely dedicated for use by buses, whilst **bus gate** describes a short bus lane often used as a short cut for public transport.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes are a key component of a high-quality bus corridor (QBC) and bus rapid transit (BRT) network, improving bus travel speeds and reliability by reducing delay caused by other traffic.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] A dedicated bus lane may occupy only part of a roadway which also has lanes serving general automotive traffic; in contrast to a transit mall which is a pedestrianized roadway also served by transit.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The first bus lane is often erroneously attributed to Chicago, where in 1939 Sheridan Road was installed with reversible lanes north of Foster Avenue.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The setup consisted of three-lanes towards the peak direction (south in the morning; north in the evening), and one contraflow lane.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] None of the lanes exclusively carried buses, but were designed to facilitate bus operations.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In 1948, the East Side Trolley Tunnel in Providence, Rhode Island was converted to bus-only use and became the first dedicated busway in the United States, continuing to operate to this day.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In 1956 Nashville became the first city to implement on-street bus lanes.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Later that year, Chicago implemented a bus lane in the center of Washington Street, a five lane one-way street downtown.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The first bus lanes in Europe were established before October 1962 when, at the creation of the UK's first contraflow bus lane, London Transport "welcomed the special bus lane idea, which is in wide use on the Continent and America".
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] An article in August 1963 identified Hamburg, Milan and Rome as having them, with Milan having 2 miles 750 yards.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Most of the lanes were with-flow, but some of the lanes in Milan and all those in Rome were contraflow.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In 1963 the tram system in Hamburg was closed and the former dedicated tram tracks were converted for bus travel.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Other large German cities soon followed, and the implementation of bus lanes was officially sanctioned in the German highway code in 1970.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Many experts from other countries (Japan among the first) studied the German example and implemented similar solutions.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] On 15 January 1964 the first bus lane in France was designated along the Quai du Louvre in Paris and the first contraflow lane was established on the old Pont de l’Alma on 15 June 1966.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The first contraflow bus lane in the UK was created in 1962 in London: a 50m-long section of Berkeley Street was made bus-only northbound while unrestricted southbound.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] A bus gate was created in 1964 as part of a one-way scheme between Vauxhall Bridge and Victoria, London.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] On 26 February 1968 the first with-flow bus lanes were put into service on Park Lane and Vauxhall Bridge in London.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] They applied from 4 p.m. - 7 p.m., Monday - Friday.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In October 1971 Runcorn opened the world's first bus rapid transitway.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Upon opening, the 7-mile (11 km) busway featured specialized stations, signal priority, grade separation, and was expanded to 14 miles (23 km) by 1980.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] By 1972 there were over 140 kilometres (87 mi) of with-flow bus lanes in 100 cities within OECD member countries, and the network grew substantially in the following decades.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The El Monte Busway between El Monte and Downtown Los Angeles was the first dedicated busway in the US, constructed in 1974.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes may be located in different locations on a street, such as on the sides of a street near the curb, or down the center.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] They may be long, continuous networks, or short segments used to allow buses to bypass bottlenecks or reduce route complexity, such as in a contraflow bus lane.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes may be demarcated in several ways.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Descriptive text such as "BUS LANE" may be marked prominently on the road surface, particularly at the beginning and end.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Some cities use a diamond-shaped pavement marking to indicate an exclusive bus lane.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The road surface may have a distinctive color, usually red, which has been shown to reduce prohibited vehicles from entering bus lanes.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Road signs may communicate when a bus lane is in effect.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes may also be physically separated from other traffic using bollards, curbs, or other raised elements.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In some cities, such as The Hague in the Netherlands, buses are allowed to use reserved tram tracks, usually laid in the middle of the road and marked with the text "Lijnbus".
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In the United Kingdom bus gates are common in towns and cities.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] A bus gate consists of a short section of road that only buses, cycles and sometimes other vehicles (typically taxis) can pass through.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] They lack most of the signage of bus lanes and have the words "BUS GATE" on the carriageway instead of "BUS LANE".
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The first bus gate in the UK is from 1964.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Buses were allowed to continue along Vauxhall Bridge Road towards Victoria while other traffic was diverted along Bessborough Road and Belgrave Road.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] A 1967 photograph shows pre-Worboys No Entry signs with "Except Buses" beneath; such signs ceased to be placed after 31 December 1964.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Until 2006 (later outside London), penalties for contravening a bus gate involved prosecution, so needed to be witnessed by police or traffic wardens.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Some local authorities sought to make bus gates self-enforcing.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Many motorists are fined for going through bus gates.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes may have separate sets of dedicated traffic signals, to allow transit signal priority at intersections.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Peak-only bus lanes are enforced only at certain times of the day, usually during rush hour, reverting to a general purpose or parking lane at other times.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Peak-only bus lanes may be in effect only in the main direction of travel, such as towards a downtown during morning rush hour traffic, with the buses using general purpose lanes in the other direction.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Entire streets can be designated as bus lanes (such as Oxford Street in London, Princes Street in Edinburgh, or Fulton Street in Downtown Brooklyn), allowing buses, taxis and delivery vehicles only, or a contra-flow bus lane can allow buses to travel in the opposite direction to other vehicles.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Some locations allow bicyclists or taxis to use bus lanes, however where bus or bicycle volumes are high, mixed traffic operations may result in uncomfortable conditions or delays.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Certain other vehicles may also be permitted in bus lanes, such as taxis, high occupancy vehicles, motorcycles, or bicycles.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Police, ambulance services and fire brigades can also use these lanes.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In the Netherlands mixed bus/cycle lanes are uncommon.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] According to the Sustainable Safety guidelines they would violate the principle of homogeneity and put road users of very different masses and speed behaviour into the same lane, which is generally discouraged.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Some locations have allowed access to bus lanes to electric cars and/or hybrid cars.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Oslo removed one such exception in 2017 following protests due to congestion in bus lanes.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The large number of electric vehicles on Norwegian roads slowed buses, defeating the purpose of bus lanes.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes can become ineffective if weak enforcement allows use by unauthorized vehicles or illegal parking.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Center-running bus lanes avoid the problem of private vehicles blocking the lane by double parking for loading of passengers or cargo.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Evidence from the operation of urban arterials in Brisbane shows that a properly enforced bus lane, operating as designed without interference, can increase passenger throughput.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In 2009 and 2010 traffic surveys showed that in Brisbane on a number of urban arterials with bus and transit lanes, noncompliance rates were approaching 90%.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Following enhanced enforcement of the lanes, noncompliance rates dropped and overall efficiency of the bus and transit lanes improved with an up to 12% increase in total passenger throughput in the lane.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Average bus journey times dropped, in some cases, by up to 19%.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Some cities, including San Francisco and New York, employ automated camera enforcement, using either stationary cameras adjacent to the bus lane, or cameras on the front of buses to automatically issue citations to vehicles obstructing the bus lane.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes give priority to buses, cutting down on journey times where roads are congested with other traffic and increasing the reliability of buses.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The introduction of bus lanes can significantly assist in the reduction of air pollution.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Bus lanes marked with colored pavement have been shown to reduce intrusions into bus lanes, speeding travel time and increasing bus reliability.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] The busiest bus lane in the United States is the Lincoln Tunnel XBL (exclusive bus lane) along the Lincoln Tunnel Approach and Helix in Hudson County, New Jersey, which carries approximately 700 buses per hour during morning peak times an average of one bus every 5.1 seconds.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] In contrast, the Cross-Harbour Tunnel in Hong Kong carries 14,500 buses per day, or an average of about 605 an hour all day (not just peak times), but the bus lane must give way to all the other road users resulting in long queues of buses.
[src:mccormick-place/bus-lane] Some residents and observers criticize bus lane plans and implementations because they take space from other vehicles or require road widening, which can require the use of eminent domain.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] McCormick, a prominent member of the McCormick family of McCormick Reaper/International Harvester fame, and publisher of the *Chicago Tribune*, championed a purpose-built lakeside convention center for Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] In 1958, ground was broken for a $35 million facility that opened in November 1960, and was named after McCormick, who died in 1955.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The lead architect was Alfred Shaw, one of the architects of the Merchandise Mart.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] This building included the Arie Crown Theater, designed by Edward Durell Stone.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] It seated nearly 5,000 people and was the second largest theater (by seating capacity) in Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The 1960 exposition hall was destroyed in a fire on January 16, 1967, despite being thought fireproof by virtue of its steel-and-concrete construction.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] At the time of the fire, the building contained highly combustible exhibits, several hydrants were shut off, and there were no sprinklers on the main floor where the fire started.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Thus the fire spread quickly and destructively, taking the life of security guard Kenneth Goodman.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The fire was investigated by a team led by Rolf H.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Jensen, Professor of Fire Protection Engineering at the Illinois Institute of Technology, who went on to found RJA Group.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Many lessons were learned and building, electrical, and fire codes for the city and worldwide were amended.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Although many wanted to rebuild the hall on a different site, Chicago mayor Richard J.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Daley chose to rebuild on the foundations of the burned building.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The new design of dark steel and glass, by Gene Summers of C.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Murphy and Associates (and formerly of Mies van der Rohe's office), contrasted with the white look of the structure that had burned.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] On January 3, 1971, the replacement building, later called the East Building and now called the Lakeside Center, opened with a 300,000 square feet (28,000 m2) main exhibition hall.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The Arie Crown Theatre sustained only minor damage in the 1967 fire, and so was incorporated into the interior of the new building.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The theater, with the largest seating capacity of any active theater in Chicago (the Uptown Theatre has more seating, but is currently closed), underwent major modifications in 1997 to improve its acoustics.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] On March 27, 2020, the United States Army Corps of Engineers announced that the complex would begin transforming convention space into a 3,000-bed hospital during the COVID-19 crisis.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The $15 million project was paid for by FEMA and was scheduled for completion on April 30.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] In 2021, it was proposed to turn Lakeside Center into a Rivers Casino, as part of the Chicago Casino Proposals.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The windows at McCormick Place Lakeside Center, which make up most of the building's exterior, encompass an area of 120,000 square feet (2.75 acres).
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] In 2023, on a single night at the height of the fall bird migration, nearly 1,000 birds crashed into the building's windows and died.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The following year, Lakeside Center spent $1.2 million and three months to apply arrays of small white dots, designed to be visible to birds, using adhesive film.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] An analysis showed that the number of birds colliding with windows at the building during the fall migration season dropped by more than 95%.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The North Building, located west of Lake Shore Drive and completed in 1986, is connected to the East Building by an enclosed pedestrian bridge.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] In contrast to the dark, flat profile of the East Building, the North Building is white (as the original building was), with twelve concrete pylons on the roof which support the roof using 72 cables.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The HVAC system for the building is incorporated into the pylons and give the building the appearance of a rigged sailing ship.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The North Building has approximately 600,000 sq ft (56,000 m2) of main exhibition space.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The South Building, dedicated on December 12th, 1996, and designed by tvsdesign, contains more than 1 million sq ft (93,000 m2) of exhibition space.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] It more than doubled the space in the complex and made McCormick Place the largest convention center in the nation.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The South Building was built on the former site of the McCormick Inn, a 25-story, 619-room hotel built in 1973 as part of the McCormick City complex and demolished in 1993 when ground was broken for the South Building in May of that year.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] On August 2, 2007, McCormick Place officials opened yet another addition to the complex, the West Building, also designed by tvsdesign and costing $882 million and completed eight months ahead of schedule.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The publicly financed West Building contains 470,000 square feet (44,000 m2) of exhibit space, bringing McCormick Place's total existing exhibition space to 2.67 million square feet (248,000 m2).
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The West Building also has 250,000 square feet (23,000 m2) of meeting space, including 61 meeting rooms, as well as a 100,000 square feet (9,300 m2) ballroom, the size of a football field and one of the largest ballrooms in the world.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] McCormick Place continued to expand in October 2017 with the opening of Wintrust Arena, a 10,387-seat arena situated on Cermak Road just north of the West Building.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The new facility hosts DePaul Blue Demons men's and women's college basketball, and the WNBA's Chicago Sky.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The new arena boasts 22 suites, 479 club seats, and 2 VIP lounges.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The arena is also equipped to host concerts, sporting events, meetings, and conventions in conjunction with the rest of the McCormick Place complex.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Sporting events such as gymnastics and volleyball are also held in the McCormick Place buildings in addition to the arena.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Archival materials are held by the Ryerson & Burnham Libraries at the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The McCormick Place on the Lake 1971 Collection includes photographs, drawings and project files documenting its construction.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] South of the center is McCormick Place Bird Sanctuary, created in 2003.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The northern end includes a recreated prairie, covering the roof of the center's underground carpark, and so requiring the use of shallow-rooted plants.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] McCormick Place is served by the Chicago Transit Authority's bus and "L" (rapid transit) systems; by Metra, Chicago's commuter rail network; and by the South Shore Line, an interurban passenger rail service that runs between Chicago and South Bend, Indiana.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Metra Electric trains—which run between the Loop and points south—stop at an eponymous station underneath McCormick Place.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] South Shore trains also stop here, but only during special events, and will not board northbound nor discharge southbound passengers due to a non-compete agreement with Metra.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] 21 bus routes—which run north-south and east-west through the South and Southwest Sides, respectively—serve McCormick directly.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Cermak–McCormick Place, a station on the "L"'s Green Line, lies two blocks west of the convention center's westernmost entrance.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The McCormick Place Busway runs 2.5 miles (4.0 km) from Lower Randolph between Michigan and Columbus in downtown Chicago to the center.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] It uses the lower levels of the multilevel streets near downtown, and surface streets to follow the Metra Electric District right-of-way to outside the South Building of McCormick Place.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Opened in 2002 at a cost of $43 million, it is meant to provide an unencumbered expressway for visitors to move between downtown hotels and the convention center, but is also used by buses for Soldier Field events, public safety workers, Metra, convention contractors, and Art Institute deliveries.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] It is also used by national and international government officials as a secure route.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] It is also known as the "Mayor's Road" (as it runs to Maggie Daley Park, named after mayor Richard M.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Daley's wife), the "Bat Cave", the "Magic Road" and a "secret road".
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] Its use is administered by the Chicago OEMC (Office of Emergency Management and Communications), and regular users are granted access cards.
[src:mccormick-place/mccormick-place] The convention center advertises the road as a benefit to potential customers.
